are you getting
on these drinks?

316
00:31:11,937 --> 00:31:13,604
None as pretty as you.

317
00:31:13,606 --> 00:31:15,873
Man.

318
00:31:20,646 --> 00:31:23,280
I'm Dale, by the way.

319
00:31:23,949 --> 00:31:25,515
Giselle.

320
00:31:36,996 --> 00:31:40,497
Okay, item number 44,
what do we have?

321
00:31:41,867 --> 00:31:46,136
Residency contract
for Abigail Hildreth.

322
00:31:51,076 --> 00:31:53,510
"Abigail Hildreth."

323
00:31:53,979 --> 00:31:56,013
And what's the date on that?

324
00:31:56,015 --> 00:31:59,416
Dated August 1st, 1999.

325
00:31:59,985 --> 00:32:03,253
August 1st, 1999.

326
00:32:03,255 --> 00:32:05,122
August 1st, 1999.

327
00:32:05,124 --> 00:32:09,493
And do we have the corresponding
deposition for Mrs. Hildreth?

328
00:32:09,495 --> 00:32:11,128
Yes.

329
00:32:26,512 --> 00:32:32,249
Have you ever heard the expression,
"A watched pot never boils"?

330
00:32:38,424 --> 00:32:39,856
Here it is.

331
00:32:39,858 --> 00:32:42,292
Thank you. See?

332
00:32:42,695 --> 00:32:45,762
I've got her down as item 12.

333
00:32:45,764 --> 00:32:48,732
Date of depo, September 15th.

334
00:32:48,968 --> 00:32:50,233
September 15th.

335
00:32:50,235 --> 00:32:53,236
Fifteenth of September.

336
00:32:53,339 --> 00:32:54,404
September 15th.

337
00:32:54,406 --> 00:32:56,773
Or yeah, September 15th.

338
00:32:56,775 --> 00:33:00,444
Thank you.
Okay, item number 45.

339
00:33:06,652 --> 00:33:07,351
Jimmy?

340
00:33:07,353 --> 00:33:11,588
It's my grandma. She's old.

341
00:33:11,590 --> 00:33:13,724
I'll be right back.

342
00:33:15,394 --> 00:33:16,026
Kim?

343
00:33:16,028 --> 00:33:18,261
<i>How fast can you get downtown?</i>

344
00:33:18,263 --> 00:33:19,930
Santa Fe downtown?

345
00:33:19,932 --> 00:33:21,565
<i>Albuquerque.</i>

346
00:33:21,567 --> 00:33:22,766
Why?

347
00:33:22,768 --> 00:33:25,068
I'm at the bar at Forque.

348
00:33:25,070 --> 00:33:28,438
And I've got a live one on the hook.

349
00:33:31,443 --> 00:33:34,644
I'm on my way. What's the shot?

350
00:33:34,713 --> 00:33:36,046
Definitely two or three.

351
00:33:36,048 --> 00:33:39,016
You don't think they do?
They could.

352
00:33:39,018 --> 00:33:41,685
I know,
but they don't have to.

353
00:33:43,756 --> 00:33:47,724
That's possible, but I don't
understand why that's an issue.

354
00:33:47,726 --> 00:33:48,959
You can always go back.

355
00:33:48,961 --> 00:33:50,160
Yeah. Yeah.

356
00:33:52,898 --> 00:33:54,097
Viktor! There you are!

357
00:33:54,099 --> 00:33:56,433
So sorry I'm late.
I had to put out a few fires.

358
00:33:56,435 --> 00:33:58,101
No problem.
I made a new friend.

359
00:33:58,103 --> 00:33:59,770
Dale, my brother Viktor.
Hey, how you doing?

360
00:33:59,772 --> 00:34:02,806
Nice to meet you, Dale. Thanks
for keeping sis company.

361
00:34:02,808 --> 00:34:03,673
My pleasure.

362
00:34:03,675 --> 00:34:07,611
You need a drink.
Let's get you a drink.

363
00:34:08,647 --> 00:34:10,113
So, what do you do, Dale?

364
00:34:10,115 --> 00:34:12,015
I'm an engineer.

365
00:34:12,451 --> 00:34:14,684
Like Casey Jones, with the hat?

366
00:34:14,686 --> 00:34:18,021
No, idiot.
An engineer-engineer.

367
00:34:18,023 --> 00:34:19,423
Not an "engineer."
Dale builds things.

368
00:34:19,425 --> 00:34:22,759
I design things. Spillways
and drainage fields, mostly.

369
00:34:22,761 --> 00:34:24,461
I don't actually build them.

370
00:34:24,463 --> 00:34:25,328
Well, that's cool. Yeah.

371
00:34:25,330 --> 00:34:29,866
But you could still wear the hat, though.
Right? Nothing stopping you.

372
00:34:29,868 --> 00:34:30,567
Yeah, I guess I could.

373
00:34:30,569 --> 00:34:32,769
I'm just saying there's no rule
about that, as far as I know.

374
00:34:32,771 --> 00:34:35,839
You are such a brat!
Why the good mood?

375
00:34:35,841 --> 00:34:38,275
Did it go well today?

376
00:34:38,277 --> 00:34:40,444
Please tell me it went well.

377
00:34:40,446 --> 00:34:42,712
Yeah, it went well.

378
00:34:43,182 --> 00:34:46,083
Very well? Like, very, very?

379
00:34:46,085 --> 00:34:49,319
Beyond our wildest... Yeah.

380
00:34:49,321 --> 00:34:51,388
Whoo!

381
00:34:51,523 --> 00:34:53,657
How many of these has she had?

382
00:34:53,659 --> 00:34:55,859
I'm just
getting started, baby!

383
00:34:55,861 --> 00:34:56,793
Remember these faces, Dale!
Giselle.

384
00:34:56,795 --> 00:34:59,529
They're gonna be on the cover of
<i>Fortune Magazine,</i> January issue.

385
00:34:59,531 --> 00:35:00,764
Giselle. Please.
Dale's a good guy.

386
00:35:00,766 --> 00:35:02,766
He's not gonna do anything.
You're boring the man.

387
00:35:02,768 --> 00:35:04,468
No, no, not really.

388
00:35:04,470 --> 00:35:05,969
Thank you.

389
00:35:05,971 --> 00:35:08,472
All right, I'm off to
the little girl's room.

390
00:35:08,474 --> 00:35:12,976
Say only nice things about me
while I'm gone, okay?

391
00:35:16,915 --> 00:35:19,116
She's something.

392
00:35:19,485 --> 00:35:20,817
Yeah.

393
00:35:23,388 --> 00:35:27,824
So, Giselle was telling me you
two are starting a business?

394
00:35:29,261 --> 00:35:31,394
What exactly did she tell you?

395
00:35:31,396 --> 00:35:33,997
Nothing much.
Just something about a dotcom.

396
00:35:33,999 --> 00:35:39,369
Some way for people to hook up with
each other using the Internet?

397
00:35:40,105 --> 00:35:41,972
Look, I'm sure
you're a nice guy,

398
00:35:41,974 --> 00:35:44,841
but she was
talking out of school.

399
00:35:45,577 --> 00:35:47,177
We're full up on this thing.

400
00:35:47,179 --> 00:35:47,744
Okay.

401
00:35:47,746 --> 00:35:51,114
We sign one more investor,
we gotta go public.

402
00:35:51,116 --> 00:35:54,251
And I'm just... No.

403
00:35:54,253 --> 00:35:57,854
We cannot take anyone else on.

404
00:35:57,856 --> 00:35:59,055
No offense.

405
00:35:59,057 --> 00:36:01,224
It's okay. Yeah.

406
00:36:04,263 --> 00:36:06,129
No worries.

407
00:37:00,419 --> 00:37:02,519
Spread your arms.

408
00:37:13,799 --> 00:37:15,298
No.

409
00:37:18,270 --> 00:37:19,536
He's got a gun.

410
00:37:19,538 --> 00:37:22,405
I don't care about the gun.

411
00:38:15,060 --> 00:38:19,629
Tomorrow, you go to
the district attorney.

412
00:38:19,631 --> 00:38:24,868
And you explain to him that
my nephew's gun was yours.

413
00:38:24,870 --> 00:38:29,773
The DA will ask you, "Why you
didn't say anything before?"

414
00:38:29,775 --> 00:38:33,276
You tell him you forgot.
You were rattled.

415
00:38:33,278 --> 00:38:36,780
Make up anything you want,
I don't give a shit.

416
00:38:36,782 --> 00:38:39,015
But it's your gun.

417
00:38:41,987 --> 00:38:43,386
Let's discuss my payment.

418
00:38:43,388 --> 00:38:47,724
That time has passed.
No $5,000 for you.

419
00:38:47,726 --> 00:38:49,225
The price is $50,000.

420
00:38:49,227 --> 00:38:52,595
How about your
payment is you get to live?

421
00:38:53,165 --> 00:38:54,564
Not enough.

422
00:38:54,566 --> 00:38:57,267
You think you can
negotiate with me?

423
00:38:57,269 --> 00:39:01,805
I say the word, my nephews
go to a certain motel.

424
00:39:01,807 --> 00:39:04,140
Pay a visit to
your daughter-in-law

425
00:39:04,142 --> 00:39:06,943
and your little granddaughter.

426
00:39:06,945 --> 00:39:09,479
What do you think happens then?

427
00:39:09,981 --> 00:39:14,184
Consider your
position carefully.

428
00:39:15,087 --> 00:39:17,220
I get my money,

429
00:39:17,222 --> 00:39:20,323
or neither of us
walk out of here.

430
00:39:29,668 --> 00:39:33,136
You're willing to die for this?

431
00:39:34,606 --> 00:39:38,908
Maybe I need the $50,000
more than you do.

432
00:39:51,890 --> 00:39:56,693
How you manage to live so
long with a mouth like that?

433
00:40:01,366 --> 00:40:03,433
$50,000.

434
00:40:04,970 --> 00:40:08,104
And the gun is yours.

435
00:40:47,212 --> 00:40:48,178
He sent you?

436
00:40:48,180 --> 00:40:49,846
I volunteered.

437
00:40:50,182 --> 00:40:53,082
Only safe way for us to talk.

438
00:41:10,469 --> 00:41:13,470
You really pushed it in there.

439
00:41:16,908 --> 00:41:19,275
That thing we did?

440
00:41:19,678 --> 00:41:22,979
He finds out, we're both dead.

441
00:41:22,981 --> 00:41:25,081
You get that, right?

442
00:41:25,517 --> 00:41:27,750
What thing we did?

443
00:41:32,924 --> 00:41:35,225
What's this? $25,000.

444
00:41:35,227 --> 00:41:36,526
What for?

445
00:41:36,528 --> 00:41:40,730
We made a deal.
I didn't hold up my end.

446
00:41:41,533 --> 00:41:46,436
Your problem is coming back
sooner than we expected.

447
00:42:03,288 --> 00:42:08,258
You gonna cash that? I might
know a guy who can help.

448
00:42:08,593 --> 00:42:11,194
It's better as a souvenir.

449
00:42:11,263 --> 00:42:15,231
I figured you'd be,
maybe, I don't know,

450
00:42:15,233 --> 00:42:17,233
a touch happier this morning.

451
00:42:17,235 --> 00:42:19,502
Maybe a smidge? Possibly?

452
00:42:19,504 --> 00:42:22,305
I am. I'm totally happy.

453
00:42:22,507 --> 00:42:24,974
Why wouldn't I be?

454
00:42:26,011 --> 00:42:27,644
I...

455
00:42:29,080 --> 00:42:31,814
I had a job offer.

456
00:42:31,917 --> 00:42:34,484
Really? From where?

457
00:42:34,486 --> 00:42:37,020
Schweikart & Cokely.

458
00:42:37,255 --> 00:42:38,087
Seriously?

459
00:42:38,089 --> 00:42:39,656
Rich Schweikart
said that they would

460
00:42:39,658 --> 00:42:42,392
even pay off my
law school loans.

461
00:42:42,394 --> 00:42:43,393
That's great!

462
00:42:43,395 --> 00:42:46,195
Please let me be there
when you tell Howard.

463
00:42:46,197 --> 00:42:47,830
Please.

464
00:42:47,933 --> 00:42:49,532
So why the sad puppy eyes?

465
00:42:49,534 --> 00:42:50,867
What, you don't want that job?

466
00:42:50,869 --> 00:42:53,703
No, no, of course I do.
I mean, who wouldn't, right?

467
00:42:53,705 --> 00:42:57,373
It's a huge firm. You get
out from under Howard's thumb.

468
00:42:57,375 --> 00:42:58,174
Right. Exactly.

469
00:42:58,176 --> 00:43:03,079
Besides, HHM is looking more and
more like a dead end for me anyway.

470
00:43:03,081 --> 00:43:06,115
Exactly. So what's the problem?

471
00:43:07,285 --> 00:43:09,052
I just...

472
00:43:13,892 --> 00:43:15,592
I don't know.

473
00:43:15,594 --> 00:43:19,429
I keep thinking of you
floating in that pool.

474
00:43:20,231 --> 00:43:24,767
You knew what you wanted,
but I got in the way.

475
00:43:24,869 --> 00:43:26,970
What are you talking about?

476
00:43:26,972 --> 00:43:30,974
You took the Davis &
Main job because of me.

477
00:43:30,976 --> 00:43:34,143
I took that job because it
was the right decision.

478
00:43:34,145 --> 00:43:35,745
A steady pay check? Done.

479
00:43:35,747 --> 00:43:40,049
A place to live that's more than,
five square feet? Boom.

480
00:43:40,051 --> 00:43:42,385
A car that's all one color?
Nailed it.

481
00:43:42,387 --> 00:43:46,556
I'm good.
I got what I wanted.

482
00:43:46,558 --> 00:43:48,157
And you?
With this Schweikart thing?

483
00:43:48,159 --> 00:43:50,927
You could have
everything you ever wanted.

484
00:43:50,929 --> 00:43:53,663
What's not to love about that?

485
00:43:55,166 --> 00:43:58,501
Yeah. What's not to love?

